What do the following options do?
a.    -0 -> specify ASCII char in octal to replace newline
b.    -s -> specify own option
c.    -w -> warning
d.    -x -> extract perl syntax inside a text
e.    -n -> operate on each line in files specified

What happens when -l and -0 are both specified, and
a.    -l appears first?
b.    -0 appears first?
-> -l appears first

Why do the -i and -n options destroy input files when included together?
-> edit in place

How does the C preprocessor distinguish between preprocessor commands and Perl comments?
-> it can't

How does the Perl interpreter distinguish options for the interpreter from options for the program itself?
-> before program name: interpreter options
-> after program name: program options
